# 3. Single Node vs Cluster - Choosing Your Mode

## 3.1 Comparison diagram

![](./media/image2.png)

*Diagram 2 : Single mode (one binary) vs Cluster mode (3 separate components) - LLM decision criteria*

## 3.2 Decision criteria for an LLM context

| **Criteria**       | **Single mode**                 | **Cluster mode**                          |
|--------------------|---------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| Active metrics     | \< 1M (recommended \< 500k)     | \> 500k, theoretically unlimited          |
| LLM requests/s     | \< 500 rps                      | \> 500 rps or intensive multi-tenant      |
| High availability  | Not native (external solutions) | Native: replicas per component            |
| LLM models in prod | 1 to 10 models                  | \> 10 models or \> 50 tenants             |
| Deployment         | 1 container / 1 binary          | 3 Kubernetes deployments minimum          |
| Retention          | Configurable, identical         | Configurable per tier (hot/warm/cold)     |
| Ops complexity     | Very low                        | Moderate to high                          |
| RAM required       | 1-4 GB depending on load        | 4 GB+ per component                       |
| License            | Open source (Apache 2.0)        | Open source (vminsert/vmstorage/vmselect) |

> **Migration rule: Single to Cluster**
>
> Migrate when: active metrics > 500k OR P99 write latency > 50ms OR HA SLA required.
>
> Migration is non-destructive: same data format, same API, same Grafana dashboards.
>
> Procedure: vmstorage snapshot -> restore on new cluster. Zero downtime possible with vmagent.

