# 15. Production case studies

This section presents three real production architectures deployed between 2024 and 2026. Each case combines VictoriaMetrics with a different LLM stack and illustrates real choices around cardinality, retention and alerting.

## 15.1 Case 1: internal RAG support chatbot (800-employee SMB)

Context: tier-1 support assistant based on Mistral 7B hosted internally, weekly indexing of 12,000 Confluence documents, 600 requests/day.

### Metrics stack

• VictoriaMetrics Single (1 VM, 4 vCPU / 8 GB RAM, 250 GB SSD)

• OTel Collector as sidecar to the LLM API

• Grafana OSS, 1 dashboard, 1 read-only user for management

• VMAlert with 4 rules, Microsoft Teams webhook output

### Observed cardinality

| **Metric**              | **Cardinality** | **Notes**                    |
|-------------------------|-----------------|------------------------------|
| llm_request_duration_ms | 120 series      | model x pipeline x status    |
| rag_retrieval_score_avg | 8 series        | 1 per index_id               |
| llm_tokens_total        | 60 series       | model x type                 |
| DCGM_FI_DEV_GPU_UTIL    | 4 series        | 2 L4 GPUs                    |
| TOTAL ACTIVE            | ~ 4,200 series  | Far below Single mode limits |

### Lessons learned

• No need for Cluster mode for at least 6 months, Single handles the load.

• Recording rules are essential for hourly cost (otherwise Grafana slows down at month end).

• Most valuable alert: RAGIndexDrift after each Confluence reindexing.

## 15.2 Case 2: multi-tenant LLM platform (B2B SaaS, 40 customers)

Context: conversational agent platform leased to 40 companies, mix of OpenAI / Anthropic / internal Llama 3 70B model on 8 H100 GPUs.

### Metrics stack

• VictoriaMetrics Cluster (3 vmstorage, 2 vminsert, 2 vmselect)

• Dedicated vmagent per zone (EU-West, US-East)

• Grafana Enterprise with per-tenant Teams and RBAC

• VMAlert: 14 rules including 5 per tenant (budget, latency, quality)

### Critical label choices

> **Key decision**
>
> tenant_id only on cost and quality metrics. On latency and error metrics, aggregate by environment (prod / staging) and model. This divides cardinality by 8.

| **Retention policy** | **Metrics** | **Justification** |
|---|---|---|
| 3 years | llm_cost_usd_total, llm_tokens_total | Billing, accounting audit |
| 12 months | rag_retrieval_score_avg, hallucination_rate | Long-term quality drift detection |
| 3 months | DCGM_*, vllm_*, raw latency | Short-term capacity planning |
| 7 days | *_debug, *_temp | Incident investigation |

## 15.3 Case 3: batch evaluation pipeline (R&D laboratory)

Context: ML team evaluating 12 prompt variants per week on 5 candidate models, 50,000 prompts per run, exports to Phoenix/Arize for LLM traces.

### Specific architecture

• VictoriaMetrics Single in push mode (vmagent receives batches via remote_write)

• No Grafana, dashboards generated in Python (Plotly) after each run

• Run metadata in labels: run_id, prompt_template_id, model_version

• Short retention (90 days), daily export to BigQuery for long-term analysis

> **Anti-pattern to avoid**
>
> NEVER push run_id directly as a label on real-time metrics. Use an external info-style metric llm_run_metadata{run_id, prompt_template_id} = 1 and join with group_left() in MetricsQL.

