# 16. Migrating from Prometheus

VictoriaMetrics is a drop-in replacement for Prometheus in 95% of cases. This section describes the migration in 5 steps, with no service interruption and no data loss.

## 16.1 Pre-migration inventory

• List all current Prometheus sources (scrapers, remote_write).

• Measure current cardinality: promtool tsdb stats /var/lib/prometheus/data/

• List all Grafana dashboards pointing to Prometheus.

• List all Prometheus rules (alerting + recording).

• Identify queries using advanced PromQL functions (rare but possible).

## 16.2 Dual-write strategy (zero downtime)

For 2 to 4 weeks, write metrics simultaneously to Prometheus and VictoriaMetrics. This lets you compare both backends with no risk.

> # prometheus.yml: add remote_write to VictoriaMetrics
>
> remote_write:
>
> - url: http://victoriametrics:8428/api/v1/write
>
> queue_config:
>
> capacity: 10000
>
> max_shards: 30
>
> max_samples_per_send: 5000
>
> batch_send_deadline: 5s

## 16.3 Historical data import from Prometheus

To preserve history without starting fresh, use vmctl:

> # Direct import from Prometheus data dir
>
> vmctl prometheus \
>
> --prom-snapshot=/var/lib/prometheus/snapshots/20260101T000000Z-abc \
>
> --vm-addr=http://victoriametrics:8428 \
>
> --vm-concurrency=8 \
>
> --vm-batch-size=10000
>
> # Verify in vmui:
>
> # http://victoriametrics:8428/vmui/?g0.expr=count(up)

## 16.4 Grafana dashboard migration

Two options based on dashboard fleet complexity:

• Simple option: change the URL of the existing Prometheus datasource. 100% of dashboards keep working (PromQL is a subset of MetricsQL).

• Recommended option: add a new VictoriaMetrics datasource (native plugin), migrate dashboards one by one and remove the Prometheus datasource when dual-write stops.

## 16.5 Final cutover and measured benefits

| **Metric** | **Before (Prometheus)** | **After (VictoriaMetrics)** | **Gain** |
|---|---|---|---|
| RAM used | 14 GB | 3 GB | -78 % |
| Disk (90d retention) | 120 GB | 16 GB | -86 % |
| Query latency P99 | 850 ms | 180 ms | -78 % |
| Supported cardinality | 1.2 M (saturates) | 10 M+ (stable) | x 8 |
| Monthly infra cost | 780 EUR | 190 EUR | -75 % |

> **Customer feedback (private bank, Brussels)**
>
> Migration of 4 Prometheus instances (federation) to 1 VictoriaMetrics Cluster. Total time: 6 weeks, of which 4 in dual-write. Zero incidents, annual savings of 7,200 EUR on monitoring infrastructure.

**MODULE 17**

# 17. SLO and SLA for LLM workloads

A Service Level Objective (SLO) translates a business requirement into a measurable metric. For LLMs, classic SLOs (uptime, latency) still apply but are not enough: you must add quality, cost and freshness.

## 17.1 5-category LLM SLO model

| **Category**        | **Indicator (SLI)**                                                     | **Typical SLO** | **Window**     |
|---------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------|----------------|
| Availability        | 1 - rate(llm_errors\[5m\]) / rate(llm_requests\[5m\])                   | 99.5 %          | 30 days        |
| Interactive latency | histogram_quantile(0.95, llm_ttft_ms)                                   | \< 1,200 ms     | 7 days         |
| Batch latency       | histogram_quantile(0.99, llm_request_duration_ms)                       | \< 8,000 ms     | 30 days        |
| Retrieval quality   | avg(rag_retrieval_score_avg)                                            | \> 0.78         | 24h            |
| Cost per request    | increase(llm_cost_usd_total\[1h\]) / increase(llm_requests_total\[1h\]) | \< 0.012 EUR    | Calendar month |

## 17.2 Error budget calculation

The error budget is the complement to 100% of the SLO. For 99.5% availability over 30 days, the error budget is 0.5% which equals 3h36 of tolerated downtime per month.

> # Error budget consumed over the SLO window (in %)
>
> (
>
> 1
>
> -
>
> (
>
> sum(increase(llm_requests_total[30d]))
>
> -
>
> sum(increase(llm_errors_total[30d]))
>
> )
>
> /
>
> sum(increase(llm_requests_total[30d]))
>
> ) / 0.005 * 100

## 17.3 Burn rate alerts (Google SRE pattern)

Alert when the error budget is being consumed too fast, with two windows to reduce false positives:

> - alert: LLMFastBurn
>
> expr: |
>
> (
>
> sum(rate(llm_errors_total[1h])) / sum(rate(llm_requests_total[1h]))
>
> ) > (14.4 * 0.005)
>
> and
>
> (
>
> sum(rate(llm_errors_total[5m])) / sum(rate(llm_requests_total[5m]))
>
> ) > (14.4 * 0.005)
>
> for: 2m
>
> labels:
>
> severity: critical
>
> annotations:
>
> summary: "Error budget burn rate 14.4x normal (exhausted in 2 days)"
>
> - alert: LLMSlowBurn
>
> expr: |
>
> (
>
> sum(rate(llm_errors_total[6h])) / sum(rate(llm_requests_total[6h]))
>
> ) > (6 * 0.005)
>
> for: 15m
>
> labels:
>
> severity: warning

